## 1. What is a Linear Model?

A **linear model** predicts $y$ as a weighted sum of features:

$$y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1 + \beta_2 x_2 + \cdots + \beta_p x_p + \varepsilon$$

| Symbol | Meaning |
|---|---|
| $\beta_0$ | Intercept (bias) |
| $\beta_j$ | Weight/coefficient for feature $x_j$ |
| $\varepsilon$ | Random noise, $\varepsilon \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2)$ |

> **Linear** means linear in the *parameters* $\beta$, not necessarily the features — you can include $x^2$, $\log x$, etc.

---

## 2. Simple Linear Regression

$$\hat{y} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x$$

Estimates:

$$\hat{\beta}_1 = \frac{\text{Cov}(x, y)}{\text{Var}(x)}, \qquad \hat{\beta}_0 = \bar{y} - \hat{\beta}_1 \bar{x}$$

---

## 3. Multiple Linear Regression

$$\hat{y} = \beta_0 + \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_j$$

In **matrix form** (compact notation for $n$ samples):

$$\mathbf{y} = \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta} + \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}$$

where $\mathbf{X}$ is the $n \times (p+1)$ design matrix with a leading column of 1s.

---

## 4. Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)

Minimises the **sum of squared residuals**:

$$\text{RSS} = \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2$$

Closed-form solution (**Normal Equations**):

$$\boxed{\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}} = (\mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{X})^{-1} \mathbf{X}^\top \mathbf{y}}$$

> **Gauss–Markov:** OLS gives the Best Linear Unbiased Estimator (BLUE) when model assumptions hold.

---

## 5. Assumptions

| # | Assumption | What breaks if violated |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Linearity | Biased predictions |
| 2 | No perfect multicollinearity | Unstable / exploding coefficients |
| 3 | Zero-mean errors | Biased intercept |
| 4 | Homoscedasticity (constant variance) | Inefficient estimates, wrong SEs |
| 5 | No autocorrelation | Wrong standard errors |
| 6 | Normal errors *(for inference only)* | Unreliable p-values / CIs |

### Diagnosing Violations

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[Fit Model] --> B[Residuals vs Fitted]
    A --> C[Q-Q Plot]
    A --> D[Scale-Location Plot]
    A --> E[VIF per Feature]

    B -->|Pattern| F[Non-linearity → add polynomial terms]
    B -->|Funnel| G[Heteroscedasticity → WLS or transform]
    C -->|Deviation| H[Non-normal errors → robust regression]
    E -->|VIF ≥ 10| I[Multicollinearity → drop or combine features]
```

---

## 6. Logistic Regression

For **binary classification** ($y \in \{0,1\}$), model the probability via the sigmoid:

$$P(y=1 \mid \mathbf{x}) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-\boldsymbol{\beta}^\top \mathbf{x}}}$$

**Loss — Binary Cross-Entropy:**

$$\mathcal{L} = -\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left[y_i \log \hat{p}_i + (1-y_i)\log(1-\hat{p}_i)\right]$$

Optimised with **gradient descent** (no closed form):

$$\boldsymbol{\beta} \leftarrow \boldsymbol{\beta} - \eta \,\nabla_{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \mathcal{L}$$

---

## 7. Model Evaluation

### Regression

| Metric | Formula | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| **MSE** | $\frac{1}{n}\sum(y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2$ | Penalises large errors |
| **RMSE** | $\sqrt{\text{MSE}}$ | Same units as $y$ |
| **MAE** | $\frac{1}{n}\sum\|y_i - \hat{y}_i\|$ | Robust to outliers |
| **R²** | $1 - \frac{\text{RSS}}{\text{TSS}}$ | Proportion of variance explained |

### Classification

| Metric | Formula |
|---|---|
| **Accuracy** | $(TP+TN)/(TP+TN+FP+FN)$ |
| **Precision** | $TP/(TP+FP)$ |
| **Recall** | $TP/(TP+FN)$ |
| **F1** | $2 \cdot \frac{\text{Precision} \cdot \text{Recall}}{\text{Precision}+\text{Recall}}$ |

