## 9. Ridge Regression

### Why?
OLS coefficients blow up when features are correlated (**multicollinearity**). Ridge shrinks them by adding an L2 penalty.

### Objective

$$J_{\text{ridge}} = \underbrace{\|\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}\|^2}_{\text{fit}} + \underbrace{\lambda\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\|_2^2}_{\text{L2 penalty}}$$

Closed-form solution:

$$\hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_{\text{ridge}} = (\mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{X} + \lambda\mathbf{I})^{-1}\mathbf{X}^\top\mathbf{y}$$

> Adding $\lambda\mathbf{I}$ guarantees the matrix is always invertible.

### Key Properties

| | Ridge |
|---|---|
| Sparsity | ❌ Never exact zeros — all features kept |
| Closed form | ✅ Yes |
| Best for | Multicollinearity, all features relevant |
| Hyperparameter | $\lambda$ (larger → more shrinkage) |

### Bias–Variance Trade-off

- **Large λ** → more bias, less variance (underfitting risk)
- **Small λ** → less bias, more variance (overfitting risk)
- Optimal λ found via **cross-validation**

```
Coefficient value
▲
│ ──────────────╲       β₁
│               ╲──── β₂       (all shrink toward 0,
│                  ╲── β₃       none reach exactly 0)
│
└──────────────────────────► λ
  small λ (≈ OLS)    large λ
```

---

## 10. Lasso Regression

### Why?
Lasso uses an L1 penalty which **zeros out** irrelevant features — automatic feature selection.

### Objective

$$J_{\text{lasso}} = \|\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}\|^2 + \lambda\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\|_1$$

No closed form — solved with **coordinate descent** using the soft-threshold update:

$$\hat{\beta}_j \leftarrow \text{sign}(z_j)\,\max(|z_j| - \tau,\; 0)$$

where $z_j$ is the simple OLS estimate for $\beta_j$ given all other coefficients fixed.

> The $\max(\cdot, 0)$ is what creates **exact zeros** — if the signal is weaker than the penalty, the coefficient is killed entirely.

### Key Properties

| | Lasso |
|---|---|
| Sparsity | ✅ Exact zeros — built-in feature selection |
| Closed form | ❌ No |
| Best for | Many irrelevant features, high-dimensional data |
| Hyperparameter | $\lambda$ |

```
Coefficient value
▲
│ ──────────╲       β₁ (survives)
│            ╲
│       ───────X── 0   β₂ (zeroed out at this λ)
│
│  ────────────────X── 0   β₃ (zeroed out early)
│
└──────────────────────────► λ
  small λ (≈ OLS)    large λ
```

---

## 11. Lasso vs Ridge

### Geometric Intuition

The fundamental difference: the **shape of the constraint region**.

```
Ridge (L2 — circle)          Lasso (L1 — diamond)

      β₂                            β₂
       ▲                             ▲
       │   ● OLS                     │   ● OLS
       │  /                          │  /
       │ ○  ← tangency on            │ ◆ ← tangency at corner
       │    smooth curve             │   → β₁ = 0 exactly!
       └───────────► β₁              └───────────► β₁
   No exact zeros                Corners on axes → exact zeros
```

### When to Use Which

| Situation | Prefer |
|---|---|
| All features are relevant | **Ridge** |
| Many irrelevant features | **Lasso** |
| Correlated features, want groups | **Elastic Net** |
| $p \gg n$ | **Lasso** or Elastic Net |
| Need fast closed-form solution | **Ridge** |

---

## 12. Elastic Net

Combines L1 + L2 — gets **sparsity from Lasso** and **stability from Ridge**:

$$J_{\text{EN}} = \|\mathbf{y} - \mathbf{X}\boldsymbol{\beta}\|^2 + \lambda\left[\alpha\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\|_1 + \frac{(1-\alpha)}{2}\|\boldsymbol{\beta}\|_2^2\right]$$

| $\alpha = 1$ | Pure Lasso |
|---|---|
| $\alpha = 0$ | Pure Ridge |
| $0 < \alpha < 1$ | Elastic Net |

**Best for:** Correlated feature groups (Lasso arbitrarily picks one; Elastic Net selects/drops them together).

---

## 13. Choosing λ

Use **K-Fold Cross-Validation** to find the best regularisation strength:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Define λ grid\nlog-spaced e.g. 1e-4 → 1e4] --> B[K-Fold Split\nK = 5 or 10]
    B --> C[For each λ: train on K-1 folds\nvalidate on 1 fold → average error]
    C --> D[Pick λ* with lowest CV error]
    D --> E{Apply 1-SE Rule?}
    E -->|Yes — simpler model| F[Pick largest λ within\n1 std error of minimum]
    E -->|No| G[Use λ* directly]
    F & G --> H[Refit on full training set]
    H --> I[Evaluate on test set]
```

> **1-SE Rule:** Choose the simplest model (most regularised) whose CV error is within one standard error of the best — avoids over-tuning.

