## 14. Support Vector Machines

### Core Idea

SVM finds a **hyperplane** that separates two classes with the **maximum margin**.

```
          ○ ○
        ○ ○        ← class +1
  ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─   ← decision boundary  wᵀx + b = 0
        ● ●        ← class -1
      ● ● ●

  |←── margin ──→|
       = 2/‖w‖      maximise this ≡ minimise ‖w‖²
```

**Support vectors** are the points sitting exactly on the margin edges — they alone determine the hyperplane.

### Hard-Margin SVM (separable data)

$$\min_{\mathbf{w}, b}\; \frac{1}{2}\|\mathbf{w}\|^2 \quad \text{s.t.}\quad y_i(\mathbf{w}^\top\mathbf{x}_i + b) \geq 1 \;\forall i$$

### Soft-Margin SVM (real-world, non-separable)

Allow some misclassifications via **slack variables** $\xi_i \geq 0$:

$$\min_{\mathbf{w}, b}\; \frac{1}{2}\|\mathbf{w}\|^2 + C\sum_{i}\xi_i \quad \text{s.t.}\quad y_i(\mathbf{w}^\top\mathbf{x}_i + b) \geq 1 - \xi_i$$

| $C$ large | Narrow margin, fewer errors — may overfit |
|---|---|
| $C$ small | Wide margin, tolerates errors — may underfit |

### Hinge Loss View

SVM minimises **hinge loss + L2 regularisation**:

$$\min_{\mathbf{w}}\; \frac{1}{2}\|\mathbf{w}\|^2 + C\sum_{i}\max\!\left(0,\; 1 - y_i(\mathbf{w}^\top\mathbf{x}_i + b)\right)$$

---

## 15. SVM Kernels

When data isn't linearly separable, **kernels** implicitly map features to a higher-dimensional space without computing the transformation explicitly (the **kernel trick**).

The dual objective uses only dot products $\mathbf{x}_i^\top\mathbf{x}_j$ — replace with $K(\mathbf{x}_i, \mathbf{x}_j)$.

### Common Kernels

| Kernel | Formula | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| **Linear** | $\mathbf{x}_i^\top\mathbf{x}_j$ | Linearly separable data, text |
| **Polynomial** | $(\gamma\,\mathbf{x}_i^\top\mathbf{x}_j + r)^d$ | Interactions up to degree $d$ |
| **RBF / Gaussian** | $\exp(-\gamma\|\mathbf{x}_i - \mathbf{x}_j\|^2)$ | General non-linear — most popular |
| **Sigmoid** | $\tanh(\gamma\,\mathbf{x}_i^\top\mathbf{x}_j + r)$ | Neural-net-like boundary |

### RBF Tuning

- **$\gamma$ large** → narrow Gaussian → complex wiggly boundary → overfitting
- **$\gamma$ small** → wide Gaussian → smooth boundary → underfitting

### Kernel Selection Workflow

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Classification Problem] --> B{Linearly separable?}
    B -->|Yes| C[Linear SVM]
    B -->|No / Unknown| D{How many features?}
    D -->|p >> n  e.g. text| E[Linear SVM\nor Lasso + Logistic]
    D -->|p ≈ n or p < n| F[RBF Kernel SVM\ntune C and γ]
    D -->|Known polynomial\ninteractions| G[Polynomial Kernel\ntune d, γ, r]
    C & E & F & G --> H[GridSearchCV on C + kernel params]
    H --> I[5-Fold CV]
    I --> J[Pick best params → test evaluation]
```

